                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17210419-22-off114 t17210419-22-cd115"></join> last. The Prosecutor deposed, that as he was got to his Door about 10 at Night the Prisoner persuaded him to go with her to her Lodgings, that while she was gone down, one Chickley pickt his Pocket of his Purse of Money as they sat on the Bedside together, and dropt it on the Bed, not having an Opportunity to carry in off; that he making a Noise for his Money the Prisoner came up again, with Rhodes and Brown: <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="172104190004"></xptr> that he seeing his Purse of Money on the Bed, got hold of it; but the Prisoner forced it out of his Hand; and Brown fell upon him and beat him: That the Purse was afterwards found in the Salt-Box, but the Money taken out. The Prisoner denied the Fact, and in her Defence said, that the Prosecutor askt her to drink a Glass of Wine, which she refusing, he said he would follow her home, that she lived in a Publick House, and the Prosecutor call'd for a Quartern of Brandy and made her drink a Glass of it; that he would have been lewd with her, but she would not let him; whereupon he would have Chickley, who came up with another Quartern, to stay with him, and she (the Prisoner) went down, and staid a good while, till Chickley crying out Murder, she, her Landlady, and others went up; but could not prove it, nor call any to her Reputation. The Jury found her <rs id="t17210419-22-verdict116" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17210419-22-verdict116" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
